The performance issue is about reducing object allocations when scheduling tasks from a non-event-loop thread. Currently, when scheduling from a different thread, we allocate both a ScheduledFutureTask and an additional Runnable wrapper to add the task to the queue. We can eliminate the Runnable allocation by having ScheduledFutureTask handle its own queue addition when running in "enqueue mode".

Explanation:
We'll modify `ScheduledFutureTask` to have an "enqueue mode" where its `run()` method adds itself to the scheduled task queue instead of executing the user task. Then in `AbstractScheduledEventExecutor.schedule()`, instead of creating a separate Runnable for enqueueing, we'll set the task to enqueue mode and execute it directly.

